## When RelPos is stripped (programmatic AST), a multi-element list
## whose content overflows the width fully explodes: every element
## lands on its own line at +1 indent, and the closing `]` returns to
## the list's caller indent. The same-line-opener / shareIndent
## shortcut that drops the list's Nest only applies in parsed mode
## (where it preserves the user's layout) - for programmatic input
## the list's Nest is needed so width-driven explode lays each
## element consistently at one indent level.
##
## Parsed input keeps the user's single-line layout: width-driven
## breaks only fire on programmatic ASTs (no RelPos).
-- config --
width: 40
-- in.cue --
x: [1, {aaaaaaaaa: 111111111, bbbbbbbbbb: 2222222222222222}]
-- out/relpos --
x: [1, {aaaaaaaaa: 111111111, bbbbbbbbbb: 2222222222222222}]
-- out/norelpos --
x: [
	1,
	{
		aaaaaaaaa:  111111111
		bbbbbbbbbb: 2222222222222222
	},
]
